{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18514"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18514"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.61,0.03,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11243"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76183"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11243"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18514"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61686"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7422"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26091"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76183"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe femoral triangle is an important anatomical landmark in the anterior thigh. It is bounded by the inguinal ligament superiorly, sartorius muscle laterally, and adductor longus muscle medially. The triangle is traversed by the femoral nerve and femoral vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between the femoral nerve and femoral artery in the femoral triangle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Femoral nerve lies medial to the artery","Femoral nerve lies lateral to the artery","Femoral nerve lies within the femoral sheath","Femoral nerve lies posterior to the artery","Femoral nerve lies anterior to the artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral nerve lies lateral to the artery\u003C/strong\u003E in the femoral triangle (Image). This relationship is clinically important for procedures such as femoral nerve blocks and femoral arterial access.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral nerve lies medial to the artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The femoral vein lies medial to the artery, not the nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral nerve lies anterior to the artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The nerve and artery lie in the same plane deep to the fascia lata\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral nerve lies posterior to the artery\u003C/strong\u003E - Both structures lie anterior to the iliopsoas muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral nerve lies within the femoral sheath\u003C/strong\u003E - The femoral nerve travels outside the femoral sheath, which contains only the femoral artery, vein and lymphatics\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe contents of the femoral triangle from lateral to medial can be remembered using the mnemonic NAVEL (Nerve, Artery, Vein, Empty space, Lymphatics).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The femoral nerve passes deep to the inguinal ligament lateral to the femoral artery in the femoral triangle.","The femoral artery enters the thigh beneath the inguinal ligament at the midpoint between the anterior superior iliac spine and pubic symphysis.","The mnemonic NAVEL (from lateral to medial: Nerve, Artery, Vein, Empty space, Lymphatics) describes the contents of the femoral triangle."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cFemoral Triangle\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is under\u00a0Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gray545.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61686"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18514"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21386"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21386"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KG4dC39lZmB55PFpr9uK1cDG64LeE4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KG4dC39lZmB55PFpr9uK1cDG64LeE4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":797}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61686"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T09:41:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T09:42:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11243"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76183"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta